  "prompt": "Why don't Google merged Allo and Duo to make one single app?",
  "response": "The decision to ultimately discontinue Allo without merging it directly into Duo, and instead focus solely on Duo and later Google Meet, was complex and driven by a few key factors:\n\n*   **Different Core Technologies:** Allo was built upon Google Assistant and leveraged AI-powered features heavily, while Duo focused on delivering a reliable, high-quality video calling experience. The underlying architectures were quite distinct. A full merge at the code level would have been a significant engineering undertaking.\n\n*   **Conflicting Visions:** The teams behind Allo and Duo had somewhat different visions for the future of communication. Allo was intended to be a more conversational, AI-driven experience, while Duo was meant to be a simple, easy-to-use video calling app. These visions were not entirely compatible.\n\n*   **User Adoption:** Duo had significantly better user adoption than Allo. Google likely realized it was more practical to build upon an existing, successful product rather than trying to force a combination.\n\n*   **Focus and Simplicity:** Google was criticized for having too many communication apps (Hangouts, Allo, Duo, etc.), which led to user confusion. Simplifying their offerings by focusing on Duo (for video calls) and Hangouts Meet (later Google Meet) for meetings was a strategic move to reduce fragmentation.\n\n*   **Resource Allocation:** Maintaining and developing multiple similar apps requires significant resources. Consolidating efforts into a single video calling platform and a single meeting platform was a more efficient use of Google's resources.\n\nIn summary, while a direct merger of Allo and Duo might have seemed logical on the surface, the different technologies, visions, user adoption rates, and the desire for simplification all contributed to Google's decision to discontinue Allo and focus on Duo (and later merge it into Google Meet).\n",
